    <title>Combined summary - Consensus based block size retargeting algorithm (draft)</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T21:00:25.332425+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-August/010696.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The issue of increasing the block size limit in Bitcoin has been a hot topic for some time now. Several proposals have been put forth by developers to address the problem, and each proposal has received varying degrees of support and criticism from the community.One popular proposal is the Consensus-based Block Size Retargeting Algorithm, which suggests that miners should vote to increase or decrease the block size by signaling the proposed percentage increase of the "base block size limit" in the coinbase field. This proposal aims to prevent miner collusion and mining centralization while addressing Bitcoin's inability to respond quickly to rising demand. The maximum change up or down is limited to 10% of the base block size limit, with the maximum block size not exceeding 8MB.However, some users have raised concerns about this proposal, particularly with regards to miner cartel behavior and mining centralization. Others argue that technical limitations such as bandwidth should determine the optimum block size. There are also criticisms regarding the proposal to allow miners to vote on block size, as it goes against Bitcoin's security model.Another proposal that was put forth in August 2015 suggested paying a difficulty penalty to produce larger-than-limit blocks immediately for a chance at later mining larger blocks. However, concerns were raised that this would lead to collective action problems.Btc Drak, a Bitcoin developer, has proposed an alternative to BIP 100 and BIP 101 that he believes will avoid the dangers of miner centralization. Under his proposal, miners must collectively agree if they want to increase the size of blocks, and a hard cap on block size is introduced within defined parameters. Drak contends that BIP 100 and other similar proposals are unrealistic due to overly optimistic assumptions about technological growth.Gavin Andresen has raised questions about the cost of including extra transactions, and debates continue over the mechanism for activating new consensus rules and criteria for changing the block size maximum rule. It is important for the community to reach agreement on these issues to prevent a schism hardfork eventually.</summary>
